 || 0 || 3\n|-\n| 23 || style=\"text-align:left\"|{{fb|CRO}} || [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group G|G]] || 3 || 1 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 3 || \u22121 || 3\n|-\n| 24 || style=\"text-align:left\"|{{fb|ECU|1900}} || [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group G|G]] || 3 || 1 || 0 || 2 || 2 || 4 || \u22122 || 3\n|-\n| 25 || style=\"text-align:left\"|{{fb|POL}} || [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group D|D]] || 3 || 1 || 0 || 2 || 3 || 7 || \u22124 || 3\n|-\n| 26 || style=\"text-align:left\"|{{fb|URU}} || [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group A|A]] || 3 || 0 || 2 || 1 || 4 || 5 || \u22121 || 2\n|-\n| 27 || style=\"text-align:left\"|{{fb|NGA}} || [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group F|F]] || 3 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 1 || 3 || \u22122 || 1\n|-\n| 28 || style=\"text-align:left\"|{{fb|FRA}} || [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group A|A]] || 3 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 0 || 3 || \u22123 || 1\n|-\n| 29 || style=\"text-align:left\"|{{fb|TUN}} || [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group H|H]] || 3 || 0 || 1 || 2 || 1 || 5 || \u22124 || 1\n|-\n| 30 || style=\"text-align:left\"|{{fb|SVN}} || [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group B|B]] || 3 || 0 || 0 || 3 || 2 || 7 || \u22125 || 0\n|-\n| 31 || style=\"text-align:left\"|{{fb|CHN}} || [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group C|C]] || 3 || 0 || 0 || 3 || 0 || 9 || \u22129 || 0\n|-\n| 32 || style=\"text-align:left\"|{{fb|KSA}} || [[2002 FIFA World Cup Group E|E]] || 3 || 0 || 0 || 3 || 0 || 12 || \u221212 || 0\n|}\n\n==Sponsorship==\nThe sponsors of the 2002 FIFA World Cup are divided into two categories: [[FIFA World Cup]] Sponsors and [[Japan national football team|Japan]] and [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] Supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/aboutfifa/organisation/news/newsid=85933/index.html |title=News Pepsi Ambush of the FIFA World Cup stopped in its track |website=FIFA.com |date= |accessdate= 7 June 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://resources.fifa.com/mm/document/fifafacts/misc-fwcpartn/52/01/15/fs-401_01_fwc-partners.pdf|title=The Official FIFA World Cup\u2122 Partners & Sponsors since 1982|website=Resources.fifa.com|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable collapsible collapsed\" width=\"75%\"\n|-\n! colspan=3|List of sponsors for the tournament \n|-\n! [[FIFA World Cup]] sponsors !! [[Japan national football team|Japan]] sponsors !! [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]] sponsors\n|-\n|\n*[[Adidas]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.adidas-group.com/en/media/news-archive/press-releases/2000/adidas-extends-fifa-world-cup-partnership-through-2006/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=10 July 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180711040213/https://www.adidas-group.com/en/media/news-archive/press-releases/2000/adidas-extends-fifa-world-cup-partnership-through-2006/ |archive-date=11 July 2018 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n*[[Avaya]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/news/fifa-welcomes-three-new-sponsors-for-2002-fifa-world-cuptm-77969|title=2018 FIFA World Cup Russia\u2122 \u2013 News \u2013 FIFA welcomes three new sponsors for 2002 FIFA World Cup\u2122 |website=FIFA.com|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/avaya-scores-with-world-cup-2002-deal/|title=Avaya scores with World Cup 2002 deal \u2013 ZDNet|first=Nawaz|last=Marican|website=Zdnet.com|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Anheuser-Busch|Budweiser]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/world-cup-2002-global-marketing-bud-wiser-anheuser-busch-set-re-use-its-one-world-one-game-one-beer-theme-adam-leyland-looks-global-marketing/145014|title=WORLD CUP 2002: Global marketing \u2013 Bud the Wiser. With Anheuser-Busch set to re-use its One World, One Game, One Beer theme, Adam Leyland looks at the global marketing strategy that underpins it|website=Campaignlive.co.uk|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[The Coca-Cola Company|Coca-Cola]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=1998/m=1/news=coca-cola-extends-fifa-partnership-through-2006-70366.html|title=Coca-Cola extends FIFA partnership through 2006|website=FIFA.com|date=30 January 1998|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Fuji Xerox]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fujixerox.co.jp/eng/company/headline/2002/fifa.html|title=Fuji Xerox Inks Contract As 2002 FIFA World Cup Korea/JapanTM Official Partner|website=Fujixerox.co.jp|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Fujifilm]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marketingweek.com/1999/11/18/fuji-in-24m-world-cup-sponsor-deal/|title=Fuji in \u00c2\u00a324m World Cup sponsor deal \u2013 Marketing Week|website=Marketingweek.com|accessdate=10 July 2018|date=18 November 1999}}</ref>\n*[[Gillette]]\n*[[Duracell]]\n*[[Hyundai Motor Company|Hyundai]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/world-cup-2002-global-marketing-hyundai-joins-squad-hyundai-sponsoring-world-cup-first-time-adam-leyland-finds-why/145013|title=WORLD CUP 2002: Global Marketing \u2013 Hyundai joins the squad. Hyundai is sponsoring the World Cup for the first time. Adam Leyland finds out why|website=Campaignlive.co.uk|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[JVC]]\n*[[MasterCard]]\n*[[McDonald's]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businesswireindia.com/news/news-details/mcdonalds-scores-children-at-2002-fifa-world-cup-koreajapan/1131|title=McDonald's Scores for Children At the 2002 FIFA World Cup Korea/Japan|website=businesswireindia.com|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/mcdonalds-line-major-world-cup-promotion-upset/148558|title=McDonald's in line for major World Cup promotion upset|website=Campaignlive.co.uk|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Philips]]\n*[[Toshiba]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.toshiba.co.jp/about/press/2001_06/pr0701.htm|title=Toshiba : Press Releases 7 Jun, 2001|website=Toshiba.co.jp|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.questia.com/library/journal/1G1-89647981/toshiba-becomes-official-sponsor-of-fifa-world-cup|title=Toshiba Becomes Official Sponsor of FIFA World Cup. (Company Round-Up)|date=1 September 2001|journal=International Journal of Sports Marketing & Sponsorship|volume=3|issue=3|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Yahoo!]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/news/y=2001/m=9/news=yahoo-becomes-the-15th-official-partner-for-the-2002-fifa-world-cup-ko-79321.html|title=Yahoo! becomes the 15th Official Partner for the 2002 FIFA World Cup Korea/Japan\u2122|website=FIFA.com|date=11 September 2001|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportcal.com/News/PressReleases/102406?size=100,100|title=Yahoo! Becomes 15th 2002 FIFA World Cup Sponsor \u2013 News \u2013 Sportcal|website=Sportcal.com|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n|\n*[[Asahi Shimbun]]\n*[[Nippon Life Insurance]]\n*[[Nippon Telegraph and Telephone]]\n*[[Nissin Foods]]\n*[[Nomura Securities]]\n*[[NTT DoCoMo]]\n*[[Tokyo Electric Power Company]]\n*[[Tokio Marine Nichido|Tokio Marine and Fire Insurance]]\n|\n*[[Hyundai Marine & Fire Insurance|Hyundai Marine and Fire Insurance]]\n*[[KCC Corporation]]\n*[[Kookmin Bank]]\n*[[Korea Telecom]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sportcal.com/News/PressReleases/50565|title=Korea Telekom Becomes Official Partner of 2002 Fifa World Cup \u2013 News \u2013 Sportcal|website=Sportcal.com|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Korean Air]]\n*[[KTF]]\n*[[Lotte Hotels & Resorts|Lotte Hotel]]\n|}\n\n==Ticket sales problem==\nThe original domestic ticket allocation had fully sold out and the organising committee completed sales of tickets returned from the international allocation by the end of April. However, it was obvious at the opening matches that there were a significant number of empty seats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/worldcup/06/01/probe.tickets/index.html |title=FIFA to probe empty seats |work=CNN.com |publisher=Cable News Network LP |date=1 June 2002 |accessdate=10 August 2013 |first=Andrew |last=Demaria}}</ref> It was gradually revealed that the World Cup Ticketing Bureau (WCTB) still had unsold tickets in its possession. After FIFA agreed to sell this inventory, JAWOC undertook sales over telephone and WCTB handled the internet sales.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soccerphile.com/soccerphile/archives/wc2002/ne/espp.html|title=World Cup 2002 Ticket Fiasco|website=Soccerphile.com|accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref> For the second round Japan vs. Turkey match in Miyagi in particular, although it was reported by both parties that all tickets had been sold, some 700 seats remained empty.\n\n==Controversies==\nThe tournament was criticized for many poor and questionable refereeing decisions.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/soccer/world-cup/the-tragic-tale-of-byron-moreno-the-worst-referee-ever/article19110587/ |title = The tragic tale of Byron Moreno, \"the worst referee, ever\"}}</ref> South Korea in particular faced scrutiny and allegations of corruption due to the favorable decisions they received in their controversial victories over Italy in the Round of 16 and over Spain in the quarter-finals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadspin.com/italian-paper-alleges-fifa-used-corrupt-refs-to-fix-200-1707704308|title=Italian Paper Alleges FIFA Used Corrupt Refs To Fix 2002 World Cup Games|last=Haisley|first=Billy|work=Deadspin|access-date=8 March 2017|language=en-US}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Cultural event==\n[[File:\"In Search of Fresh Air\", by Ray L. Burggraf.jpg|thumb|upright|''In Search of Fresh Air''. Banner by Ray L. Burggraf.]]\nThe official FIFA cultural event of the 2002 World Cup was a flag festival called ''Poetry of the Winds''.<ref name=\"le-musee-divisioniste2002\">{{cite web|url=http://www.le-musee-divisioniste.org/service/pages/2002/flagart2.htm |title=Flag Art Festival Seoul |website=Le-musee-divisioniste.org |date=29 May 2002 |accessdate=14 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130613061908/http://www.le-musee-divisioniste.org/service/pages/2002/flagart2.htm |archivedate=13 June 2013 }}</ref> Held in [[World Cup Park#Nanjicheon Park|Nanjicheon Park]], an area of the World Cup Park close to the stadium,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fsu.edu/~svad/SVADNews1.pdf|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040328013702/http://www.fsu.edu/~svad/SVADNews1.pdf|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 March 2004|title=SVAD News|accessdate=14 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.exploringkorea.com/world-cup-park-seoul/ |title=World Cup Park Seoul Neoul Park, Haneul, Nanji Hangang, Nanjicheon, Pyeonghwa |publisher=Exploring Korea |accessdate=14 August 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130811104651/http://www.exploringkorea.com/world-cup-park-seoul/ |archivedate=11 August 2013 }}</ref> ''Poetry of the Winds'' was exhibited from 29 May to 25 June in order to wish success upon the World Cup and promote a festive atmosphere. During the flag art festival, hand-painted flags from global artists were displayed as a greeting to international guests in a manner that was designed to promote harmony (2002 Flag Art Festival Executive Committee).<ref name=\"le-musee-divisioniste2002\"/>\n\n==Aftermath and legacy==\n\nThe tournament had a major economic impact on both South Korea and Japan, generating an estimated US$1.3 billion in revenue.<ref name=\"LeeTaylor\">{{Cite journal|last=Lee|first=Choong-Ki|last2=Taylor|first2=Tracy|date=2005-08-01|title=Critical reflections on the economic impact assessment of a mega-event: the case of 2002 FIFA World Cup|journal=Tourism Management|volume=26|issue=4|pages=595\u2013603|doi=10.1016/j.tourman.2004.03.002|issn=0261-5177}}</ref> Spending from World Cup tourists in South Korea created US$307 million in direct income and US$713 million in valued added.<ref name=\"LeeTaylor\"/> Japan spent an estimated US$5.6 billion on preparations for the event, which had a US$24.8 billion impact on the Japanese economy and accounted for 0.6% of their GDP in 2002.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Handbook on the economics of sport|date=2009|publisher=Edward Elgar|others=Andreff, Wladimir, 1946-, Szymanski, Stefan, 1960-|isbn=978-1-84844-351-8|edition=Paperbk.|location=Cheltenham, UK|oclc=262720289}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Association football|Japan|South Korea}}\n* [[Adidas Fevernova]] \u2013 match ball\n* ''[[The Official Album of the 2002 FIFA World Cup]]''\n* ''[[The Doraemons]]'' movies: ''[[Goal! Goal! Goal!!]]'' (2002 FIFA World Cup movies)\n{{-}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|2002 FIFA World Cup}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20020802015509/http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/en 2002 FIFA World Cup Official Website] (archived)\n*[https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/koreajapan2002/index.html 2002 FIFA World Cup Korea/Japan \u2122], FIFA.com\n*[https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/08/41/fwc_korea_japan_2002_a_part1_265.pdf FIFA Technical Report (Part 1)] and [https://www.fifa.com/mm/document/afdeveloping/technicaldevp/50/08/38/fwc_korea_japan_2002_a_part2_264.pdf (Part 2)]\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tables/2002full.html RSSSF Archive of finals]\n*[http://www.rsssf.com/tables/2002q.html RSSSF Archive of qualifying rounds]\n\n{{2002 FIFA World Cup}}\n{{2002 FIFA World Cup stadiums}}\n{{FIFA World Cup}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:2002 FIFA World Cup| ]]\n[[Category:FIFA World Cup tournaments]]\n[[Category:International association football competitions hosted by South Korea]]\n[[Category:International association football competitions hosted by Japan]]\n[[Category:Japan\u2013South Korea relations]]\n[[Category:2002 in Japanese football|FIFA World Cup]]\n[[Category:2002 in South Korean football]]\n[[Category:May 2002 sports events in Asia]]\n[[Category:June 2002 sports events in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "2600:1700:3520:1980:cc7a:7c50:f2ee:b29c", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2002_FIFA_World_Cup"}
{"title_page": "Allu (video game player)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Pro Gaming player\n| ID            = Allu\n| name          = Aleksi Jalli\n| name_trans    = \n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| status        = Active (2009-present)\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1992|5|20}}\n| hometown      = {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| nationality   = {{flagicon|FIN}} Finnish\n| team          = {{flagicon|FIN}} [[ENCE eSports]]\n| role          = AWPer\n| league        = \n| coach         = \n| games         = ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]''\n| earnings      = \n| championships =\n| website       = \n| years1        = 2013-2014\n| team1         = {{flagicon|FIN}} [[ENCE eSports]]\n| years2        = 2014-2015\n| team2         = {{flagicon|EU}} [[Mousesports]]\n| years3        = 2015\n| team3         = {{flagicon|FIN}} 3DMAX\n| years4        = 2015\n| team4         = {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Ninjas in Pyjamas]]\n| years5        = 2016\n| team5         = {{flagicon|FIN}} [[ENCE eSports]]\n| years6        = Aug 2016-Aug 2017\n| team6         = {{flagicon|EU}} [[FaZe Clan]]\n| years7        = Aug 2017-Jan 2018\n| team7         = {{flagicon|EU}} [[OpTic Gaming]]\n| years8        = Mar 2018-present\n| team8         = {{flagicon|FIN}} [[ENCE eSports]]}}\n\n'''Aleksi Jalli''' (born May 20, 1992), better known by his in-game ID '''allu''', is a Finnish professional ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]'' player is currently playing for [[ENCE eSports]]. He previously played for [[Ninjas in Pyjamas]] and [[FaZe Clan]] as their [[AWPer]]. He has also played for 3DMax, [[mousesports]] (mouz), ENCE, Rats of the Year, [[Team Curse]], RAIDERS, The Hawks, and Team WinFakt.\n\n==Career==\n=== ''Counter-Strike 1.6'' Career ===\nallu started playing CS competitively in Finland's 1.6 scene.  He attended some notable events such as DreamHack Winter 2009, DreamHack Winter 2010, and Copenhagen Games 2011, but he never had any notable results.\n\n=== 2012/2013 ===\nallu transitioned to ''Counter-Strike: Global Offensive'' successfully, and played for some low level Finnish teams.  He evetually transitioned to ENCE, but at the time, the Finnish scene didn't have very much talent, and allu once again struggled to place.\n\n===2014===\nAllu left ENCE in June, and later the organization dropped the rest of the CS:GO roster.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/finland-counter-strike-ence/|title=The Finnish 'Counter-Strike' scene is at a crossroads|first=Jared|last=Wynne|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|date=June 30, 2014|accessdate=December 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210221722/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/finland-counter-strike-ence/|archive-date=December 10, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}\n</ref> Allu joined [[mousesports]] in July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/mousesports-counter-strike-team/|title=Mousesports finally fills out its 'Counter-Strike' roster|first=Jared|last=Wynne|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|date=July 2, 2014|accessdate=December 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210222358/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/mousesports-counter-strike-team/|archive-date=December 10, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> At [[ESWC 2014]] mouz finished 9 - 12th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toornament.com/tournaments/54311a549a6d9cc451000000/|title=Electronic Sports World Cup 2014|author=Oxent|accessdate=December 9, 2015|website=Toornament}}</ref> mouz failed to qualify for the third CS:GO Major of 2014, [[DreamHack Winter 2014]].  mouz found very minor success at smaller LANs in 2014.\n\n===2015===\nAllu left mousesports at the end of January and joined 3DMax.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/counter-strike-3dmax-allu-mousesports/|title=Allu leaves Mousesports, heads home to Finland|first=Jared|last=Wynne|website=The Daily Dot|date=January 2, 2015|accessdate=December 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210220550/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/counter-strike-3dmax-allu-mousesports/|archive-date=December 10, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> During his brief stint with the team he failed to qualify for CS:GO Major [[ESL One Katowice 2015]]. Allu joined [[Stockholm]]-based Ninjas in Pyjamas in February, replacing [[Mikail \"Maikelele\" Bill]] on what was intended to be trial basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esport.aftonbladet.se/esport/fifth-ninja/|title=Allu recruited to Ninjas in Pyjamas|first=Andjela|last=Kusmuk|website=[[Aftonbladet]] Esport|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> At 2015's first CS:GO Major, ESL One Katowice 2015, they finished second after losing to [[Fnatic]] in the finals.<ref name=\"leaves nip\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/allu-leaves-ninjas-in-pyjamas/|title=Allu leaves Ninjas in Pyjamas|first=Callum|last=Leslie|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|date=December 8, 2015|access-date=December 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210220342/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/allu-leaves-ninjas-in-pyjamas/|archive-date=December 10, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | first=Nico | last=Hartikainen | url=http://yle.fi/aihe/artikkeli/2015/02/24/allu-siirtyy-ninjas-pyjamasiin | title=allu siirtyy Ninjas in Pyjamasiin | date=February 24, 2015 | accessdate=July 6, 2016 | work=[[Yle]]}}</ref> In August the second CS:GO Major, [[ESL One Cologne 2015]], was held, and Allu and NiP finished in 5-8th. In November NiP finished 3-4th in the third Major of the year, [[DreamHack Open Cluj-Napoca 2015]]. In December NiP finished second at Fragbite Masters Season 5.<ref name=\"leaves nip\"/> Jalli left Ninjas in Pyjamas on December 8, two months before his contract was set to expire, and did not immediately join another team.<ref name=\"leaves nip\"/> After a successful individual year for allu, he claimed 19th place in the Top 20 Players of 2015 by [[hltv.org]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0160vejda |first1=Milan \"Striker\" |title=Top 20 Players of 2015: allu (19) |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/16707/top-20-players-of-2015-allu-19 |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn January 4 it was announced that allu had rejoined ENCE eSports.<ref name=\"suomalainen huippujoukkue palaa\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/esports/art-1451879447819.html |title=Suomalainen huippujoukkue palaa - Aleksi \"allu\" Jalli t\u00e4hditt\u00e4\u00e4 Counter-Strike-kokoonpanoa |author=Niko \"milA\" Hartikainen |date=2015-01-04 |website=[[Ilta-Sanomat]] eSports |language=Finnish |accessdate=2015-01-04}}</ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/esports/art-1451879447819.html |title=Suomalainen huippujoukkue palaa - Aleksi \"allu\" Jalli t\u00e4hditt\u00e4\u00e4 Counter-Strike-kokoonpanoa |author=Niko \"milA\" Hartikainen |date=2015-01-04 |website=[[Ilta-Sanomat]] eSports |language=Finnish |accessdate=2015-01-04}}</ref>  Once again, allu would not find much success with the Finnish team, and on August 16, allu transferred to [[FaZe]], replacing [[fox (video game player)|fox]] on the roster.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0160vejda |first1=Milan \"Striker\" |title=allu replaces fox in FaZe |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/18419/allu-replaces-fox-in-faze |website=HLTV |accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref>  After adding [[karrigan]], FaZe had some notable placements including a semifinals finish at IEM Oakland 2016 and [[ELEAGUE Season 2]].\n\n===2017===\nFaZe had good results in the start of 2017 with allu, placing 2nd at IEM Sydney 2017 and IEM Katowice 2017.  They placed 1st at StarLadder & i-League Season 3.  However, at [[PGL Major Krak\u00f3w 2017]], FaZe went out in last place.  In the aftermath, allu was benched from [[FaZe]], and replaced by GuardiaN.<ref>https://www.hltv.org/news/21186/guardian-replaces-allu-in-faze</ref>  Allu was soon moved to the short lived international European roster of [[OpTic Gaming]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Burazin |first1=Zvonimir \"Professeur\" |title=Optic Forms International Roster |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/21282/optic-forms-international-roster |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nIn 2018, allu once again returned to the Finnish scene and formed the Finnish team ENCE along with Aleksi \"Aleksib\" Virolainen, Jani \"Aerial\" Jussila, Sami \"xseven\" Laasanen, and Jere \"sergej\" Salo.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miles |first1=Lucas Aznar \"LucasAM\" |title=ENCE Reveal New Roster |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/23217/ence-reveal-new-roster |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>  The roster would soon find success, winning StarSeries and I-League Season 6, over [[Vega Squadron]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0160vejda |first1=Milan \"Striker\" |title=ENCE Beat Vega Squadron in Five-Map Marathon, Win StarSeries I-League Season 6 |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/25088/ence-beat-vega-squadron-in-five-map-marathon-win-starseries-i-league-season-6 |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>  At the end of 2018, allu and ENCE would win Dreamhack Winter 2018, with a great personal performance from allu.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miles |first1=Lucas Aznar \"LucasAM\" |title=ENCE Defeat Bravado to Win Dreamhack Winter |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/25530/ence-defeat-bravado-to-win-dreamhack-winter |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nIn early 2019, ENCE had a major upset<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erzberger |first1=Tyler |title=ENCE the most unlikely of IEM Katowice finalists |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/26121852/ence-most-unlikely-iem-katowice-finalists |website=ESPN |accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref> and came 2nd at the first major of the year, [[Intel Extreme Masters Season XIII \u2013 World Championship Major|IEM Katowice 2019]].<ref>{{cite web |title=IEM Katowice 2019: Results |url=https://www.hltv.org/events/3883/iem-katowice-2019 |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref> Later on in the year, they would attend StarSeries i-League Season 7, where they would place 5th-8th, falling at the hands of Natus Vincere. Following this, they would make a 3rd-place finish at Blast Pro Series S\u00e3o Paulo, going 4-1-1 in the group stage where they drew against Team Liquid and lost to Astralis. They would get revenge on the latter, however, by defeating them in a best-of-3 final at Blast Pro Series Madrid 2\u20130, taking their first LAN title of the year.  ENCE placed 2nd at DreamHack Master Dallas 2019 and IEM Chicago 2019, losing to [[Team Liquid]] in the grand finals both times.  Before the [[StarLadder Major: Berlin 2019]], ENCE were set to replace their In-Game Leader Aleksi \"Aleksib\" Virolainen with Miikaa \"suNny\" Kemppi, after the major.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aznar Miles |first1=Lucas \"LucasAM\" |title=ENCE sign suNny; Aleksib to be benched after Major |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/27613/ence-sign-sunny-aleksib-to-be-benched-after-major |website=HLTV |accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref>  Allu took over In-Game Leading duties after his departure.\n\n==Personal life==\nDuring his time on [[NiP|Ninjas In Pyjamas]], Allu mostly lived in [[Finland]], but met with his teammates in person before major tournaments. Allu is a Dad to 1 child who was born on 16 February 2019, during [[ENCE|ENCE eSports]]'s historic run at the [[IEM Katowice 2019]]<ref>https://mobile.twitter.com/alluCSGO/status/1096831180970823682?s=19</ref>\n\n==Tournament results==\n:'''Bold''' denotes a CS:GO Major\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"880\"style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Placement\n!Tournament\n!Location\n!Date\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |With [[Ninjas in Pyjamas]]\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| '''[[ESL One Katowice 2015]]'''\n| [[Katowice]], [[Poland]]\n| 2015-03-12 {{ndash}} 2015-03-15\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| Gfniity Spring Masters 1\n| [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| 2015-03-20 {{ndash}} 2015-03-22\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| StarLadder StarSeries XII \n| [[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]]\n| 2015-01-13 {{ndash}} 2015-03-29\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| FACEIT League 2015 Stage I Finals  \n| London, United Kingdom\n| 2015-05-01 {{ndash}} 2015-05-03\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| Gfinity Masters Summer 1 \n| London, United Kingdom\n| 2015-06-26 {{ndash}} 2015-06-28\n|-\n| {{Bronze3}}\n| '''[[DreamHack Open Cluj-Napoca 2015]]'''\n| [[Cluj-Napoca]], [[Romania]]\n| 2015-10-28 {{ndash}} 2015-11-01\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |With 2016's ENCE Esports\n|-\n| {{Gold1}}\n| Operation: Kinguin #2 \n| N/A\n| 2016-01-18 {{ndash}} 2016-04-20\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |With FaZe Clan\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| IEM Katowice 2017\n| Katowice, Poland\n| 2017-03-01 {{ndash}} 2017-03-05\n|-\n| {{Gold1}}\n| StarLadder i-League StarSeries Season 3\n| Kiev, Ukraine\n| 2017-04-04 {{ndash}} 2017-04-09\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| IEM Sydney 2017\n| [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n| 2017-05-03 {{ndash}} 2017-05-07\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| ECS Season 3 Finals\n| London, Unitd Kingdom\n| 2017-06-23 {{ndash}} 2017-06-25\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |With 2018's ENCE Esports\n|-\n| {{Gold1}}\n| StarSeries & i-League CS:GO Season 6 \n| Kiev, Ukraine\n| 2018-10-07 {{ndash}} 2018-10-14\n|-\n| {{Gold1}}\n| Dreamhack Open Winter 2018\n| [[J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]], [[Sweden]]\n| 2018-11-30 {{ndash}} 2018-12-02\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| [[Intel Extreme Masters Season XIII \u2013 World Championship Major|IEM Katowice 2019]]\n| Katowice, Poland\n| 2019-02-13 {{ndash}} 2019-03-03\n|-\n| {{Gold1}}\n| BLAST Pro Series: Madrid 2019 \n| [[Madrid]], [[Spain]]\n| 2019-05-10 {{ndash}} 2019-05-11\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| DreamHack Masters Dallas 2019  \n| [[Dallas]], [[United States]]\n| 2019-05-28 {{ndash}} 2019-06-02\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| IEM Chicago 2019\n| [[Chicago]], United States\n| 2019-07-18 {{ndash}} 2019-07-21\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{cite journal|journal=[[Urheilulehti]]|title=Tunnetko h\u00e4net?|date=May 6, 2016}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://twitter.com/alluCSGO Twitter account]\n* [http://www.twitch.tv/allub Twitch channel]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/allucsgo Official Facebook fan page]\n\n{{FaZe Clan}}\n{{Professional Counter-Strike competition}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Allu}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Mousesports players]]\n[[Category:Ninjas in Pyjamas players]]\n[[Category:Counter-Strike players]]\n[[Category:Finnish esports players]]\n[[Category:People from Helsinki]]\n[[Category:Team Curse players]]\n[[Category:FaZe Clan players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Pro Gaming player\n| ID            = Allu\n| name          = Aleksi Jalli\n| name_trans    = \n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| status        = Active (2009-present)\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1992|5|20}}\n| hometown      = {{flagicon|FIN}} [[Helsinki]], [[Finland]]\n| nationality   = {{flagicon|FIN}} Finnish\n| team          = {{flagicon|FIN}} [[ENCE eSports]]\n| role          = AWPer\n| league        = \n| coach         = \n| games         = ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]''\n| earnings      = \n| championships =\n| website       = \n| years1        = 2013-2014\n| team1         = {{flagicon|FIN}} [[ENCE eSports]]\n| years2        = 2014-2015\n| team2         = {{flagicon|EU}} [[Mousesports]]\n| years3        = 2015\n| team3         = {{flagicon|FIN}} 3DMAX\n| years4        = 2015\n| team4         = {{flagicon|SWE}} [[Ninjas in Pyjamas]]\n| years5        = 2016\n| team5         = {{flagicon|FIN}} [[ENCE eSports]]\n| years6        = Aug 2016-Aug 2017\n| team6         = {{flagicon|EU}} [[FaZe Clan]]\n| years7        = Aug 2017-Jan 2018\n| team7         = {{flagicon|EU}} [[OpTic Gaming]]\n| years8        = Mar 2018-present\n| team8         = {{flagicon|FIN}} [[ENCE eSports]]}}\n\n'''Aleksi Jalli''' (born May 20, 1992), better known by his in-game ID '''allu''', is a Finnish professional ''[[Counter-Strike: Global Offensive]]'' player is currently playing for [[ENCE eSports]]. He previously played for [[Ninjas in Pyjamas]] and [[FaZe Clan]] as their [[AWPer]]. He has also played for 3DMax, [[mousesports]] (mouz), ENCE, Rats of the Year, [[Team Curse]], RAIDERS, The Hawks, and Team WinFakt.\n\n==Career==\n=== ''Counter-Strike 1.6'' Career ===\nallu started playing CS competitively in Finland's 1.6 scene.  He attended some notable events such as DreamHack Winter 2009, DreamHack Winter 2010, and Copenhagen Games 2011, but he never had any notable results.\n=== 2012/2013 ===\nallu transitioned to ''Counter-Strike: Global Offensive'' successfully, and played for some low level Finnish teams.  He evetually transitioned to ENCE, but at the time, the Finnish scene didn't have very much talent, and allu once again struggled to place.\n===2014===\nAllu left ENCE in June, and later the organization dropped the rest of the CS:GO roster.<ref>\n{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/finland-counter-strike-ence/|title=The Finnish 'Counter-Strike' scene is at a crossroads|first=Jared|last=Wynne|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|date=June 30, 2014|accessdate=December 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210221722/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/finland-counter-strike-ence/|archive-date=December 10, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}\n</ref> Allu joined [[mousesports]] in July 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/mousesports-counter-strike-team/|title=Mousesports finally fills out its 'Counter-Strike' roster|first=Jared|last=Wynne|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|date=July 2, 2014|accessdate=December 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210222358/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/mousesports-counter-strike-team/|archive-date=December 10, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> At [[ESWC 2014]] mouz finished 9 - 12th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toornament.com/tournaments/54311a549a6d9cc451000000/|title=Electronic Sports World Cup 2014|author=Oxent|accessdate=December 9, 2015|website=Toornament}}</ref> mouz failed to qualify for the third CS:GO Major of 2014, [[DreamHack Winter 2014]].  mouz found very minor success at smaller LANs in 2014.\n\n===2015===\nAllu left mousesports at the end of January and joined 3DMax.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/counter-strike-3dmax-allu-mousesports/|title=Allu leaves Mousesports, heads home to Finland|first=Jared|last=Wynne|website=The Daily Dot|date=January 2, 2015|accessdate=December 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210220550/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/counter-strike-3dmax-allu-mousesports/|archive-date=December 10, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> During his brief stint with the team he failed to qualify for CS:GO Major [[ESL One Katowice 2015]]. Allu joined [[Stockholm]]-based Ninjas in Pyjamas in February, replacing [[Mikail \"Maikelele\" Bill]] on what was intended to be trial basis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esport.aftonbladet.se/esport/fifth-ninja/|title=Allu recruited to Ninjas in Pyjamas|first=Andjela|last=Kusmuk|website=[[Aftonbladet]] Esport|date=February 24, 2015}}</ref> At 2015's first CS:GO Major, ESL One Katowice 2015, they finished second after losing to [[Fnatic]] in the finals.<ref name=\"leaves nip\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dailydot.com/esports/allu-leaves-ninjas-in-pyjamas/|title=Allu leaves Ninjas in Pyjamas|first=Callum|last=Leslie|website=[[The Daily Dot]]|date=December 8, 2015|access-date=December 9, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151210220342/http://www.dailydot.com/esports/allu-leaves-ninjas-in-pyjamas/|archive-date=December 10, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | first=Nico | last=Hartikainen | url=http://yle.fi/aihe/artikkeli/2015/02/24/allu-siirtyy-ninjas-pyjamasiin | title=allu siirtyy Ninjas in Pyjamasiin | date=February 24, 2015 | accessdate=July 6, 2016 | work=[[Yle]]}}</ref> In August the second CS:GO Major, [[ESL One Cologne 2015]], was held, and Allu and NiP finished in 5-8th. In November NiP finished 3-4th in the third Major of the year, [[DreamHack Open Cluj-Napoca 2015]]. In December NiP finished second at Fragbite Masters Season 5.<ref name=\"leaves nip\"/> Jalli left Ninjas in Pyjamas on December 8, two months before his contract was set to expire, and did not immediately join another team.<ref name=\"leaves nip\"/>After a successful individual year for allu, he claimed 19th place in the Top 20 Players of 2015 by [[hltv.org]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0160vejda |first1=Milan \"Striker\" |title=Top 20 Players of 2015: allu (19) |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/16707/top-20-players-of-2015-allu-19 |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nOn January 4 it was announced that allu had rejoined ENCE eSports.<ref name=\"suomalainen huippujoukkue palaa\">{{cite web |url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/esports/art-1451879447819.html |title=Suomalainen huippujoukkue palaa - Aleksi \"allu\" Jalli t\u00e4hditt\u00e4\u00e4 Counter-Strike-kokoonpanoa |author=Niko \"milA\" Hartikainen |date=2015-01-04 |website=[[Ilta-Sanomat]] eSports |language=Finnish |accessdate=2015-01-04}}</ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iltasanomat.fi/esports/art-1451879447819.html |title=Suomalainen huippujoukkue palaa - Aleksi \"allu\" Jalli t\u00e4hditt\u00e4\u00e4 Counter-Strike-kokoonpanoa |author=Niko \"milA\" Hartikainen |date=2015-01-04 |website=[[Ilta-Sanomat]] eSports |language=Finnish |accessdate=2015-01-04}}</ref>  Once again, allu would not find much success with the Finnish team, and on August 16, allu transferred to [[FaZe]], replacing [[fox (video game player)|fox]] on the roster.<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0160vejda |first1=Milan \"Striker\" |title=allu replaces fox in FaZe |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/18419/allu-replaces-fox-in-faze |website=HLTV |accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref>  After adding [[karrigan]], FaZe had some notable placements including a semifinals finish at IEM Oakland 2016 and [[ELEAGUE Season 2]].\n\n===2017===\nFaZe had good results in the start of 2017 with allu, placing 2nd at IEM Sydney 2017 and IEM Katowice 2017.  They placed 1st at StarLadder & i-League Season 3.  However, at [[PGL Major Krak\u00f3w 2017]], FaZe went out in last place.  In the aftermath, allu was benched from [[FaZe]], and replaced by GuardiaN.<ref>https://www.hltv.org/news/21186/guardian-replaces-allu-in-faze</ref>  Allu was soon moved to the short lived international European roster of [[OpTic Gaming]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Burazin |first1=Zvonimir \"Professeur\" |title=Optic Forms International Roster |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/21282/optic-forms-international-roster |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\nIn 2018, allu once again returned to the Finnish scene and formed the Finnish team ENCE along with Aleksi \"Aleksib\" Virolainen, Jani \"Aerial\" Jussila, Sami \"xseven\" Laasanen, and Jere \"sergej\" Salo.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miles |first1=Lucas Aznar \"LucasAM\" |title=ENCE Reveal New Roster |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/23217/ence-reveal-new-roster |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>  The roster would soon find success, winning StarSeries and I-League Season 6, over [[Vega Squadron]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=\u0160vejda |first1=Milan \"Striker\" |title=ENCE Beat Vega Squadron in Five-Map Marathon, Win StarSeries I-League Season 6 |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/25088/ence-beat-vega-squadron-in-five-map-marathon-win-starseries-i-league-season-6 |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>  At the end of 2018, allu and ENCE would win Dreamhack Winter 2018, with a great personal performance from allu.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Miles |first1=Lucas Aznar \"LucasAM\" |title=ENCE Defeat Bravado to Win Dreamhack Winter |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/25530/ence-defeat-bravado-to-win-dreamhack-winter |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nIn early 2019, ENCE had a major upset<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erzberger |first1=Tyler |title=ENCE the most unlikely of IEM Katowice finalists |url=https://www.espn.com/esports/story/_/id/26121852/ence-most-unlikely-iem-katowice-finalists |website=ESPN |accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref> and came 2nd at the first major of the year, [[Intel Extreme Masters Season XIII \u2013 World Championship Major|IEM Katowice 2019]].<ref>{{cite web |title=IEM Katowice 2019: Results |url=https://www.hltv.org/events/3883/iem-katowice-2019 |website=hltv.org |accessdate=30 March 2019}}</ref> Later on in the year, they would attend StarSeries i-League Season 7, where they would place 5th-8th, falling at the hands of Natus Vincere. Following this, they would make a 3rd place finish at Blast Pro Series Sao Paulo, going 4-1-1 in the group stage where they drew against Team Liquid and lost to Astralis. They would get revenge on the latter, however, by defeating them in a best-of-3 final at Blast Pro Series Madrid 2-0, taking their first LAN title of the year.  ENCE placed 2nd at DreamHack Master Dallas 2019 and IEM Chicago 2019, losing to [[Team Liquid]] in the grand finals both times.  Before the [[StarLadder Major: Berlin 2019]], ENCE were set to replace their In-Game Leader Aleksi \"Aleksib\" Virolainen with Miikaa \"suNny\" Kemppi, after the major.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Aznar Miles |first1=Lucas \"LucasAM\" |title=ENCE sign suNny; Aleksib to be benched after Major |url=https://www.hltv.org/news/27613/ence-sign-sunny-aleksib-to-be-benched-after-major |website=HLTV |accessdate=8 September 2019}}</ref>  Allu took over In-Game Leading duties after his departure.\n\n==Personal life==\nDuring his time on [[NiP|Ninjas In Pyjamas]], Allu mostly lived in [[Finland]], but met with his teammates in person before major tournaments. Allu is a Dad to 1 child who was born on 16th February 2019, during [[ENCE|ENCE eSports]]'s historic run at the [[IEM Katowice 2019]]<ref>https://mobile.twitter.com/alluCSGO/status/1096831180970823682?s=19</ref>\n\n==Tournament results==\n:'''Bold''' denotes a CS:GO Major\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=\"880\"style=\"text-align:center\"\n!Placement\n!Tournament\n!Location\n!Date\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |With [[Ninjas in Pyjamas]]\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| '''[[ESL One Katowice 2015]]'''\n| [[Katowice]], [[Poland]]\n| 2015-03-12 {{ndash}} 2015-03-15\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| Gfniity Spring Masters 1\n| [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| 2015-03-20 {{ndash}} 2015-03-22\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| StarLadder StarSeries XII \n| [[Kiev]], [[Ukraine]]\n| 2015-01-13 {{ndash}} 2015-03-29\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| FACEIT League 2015 Stage I Finals  \n| London, United Kingdom\n| 2015-05-01 {{ndash}} 2015-05-03\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| Gfinity Masters Summer 1 \n| London, United Kingdom\n| 2015-06-26 {{ndash}} 2015-06-28\n|-\n| {{Bronze3}}\n| '''[[DreamHack Open Cluj-Napoca 2015]]'''\n| [[Cluj-Napoca]], [[Romania]]\n| 2015-10-28 {{ndash}} 2015-11-01\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |With 2016's ENCE Esports\n|-\n| {{Gold1}}\n| Operation: Kinguin #2 \n| N/A\n| 2016-01-18 {{ndash}} 2016-04-20\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |With FaZe Clan\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| IEM Katowice 2017\n| Katowice, Poland\n| 2017-03-01 {{ndash}} 2017-03-05\n|-\n| {{Gold1}}\n| StarLadder i-League StarSeries Season 3\n| Kiev, Ukraine\n| 2017-04-04 {{ndash}} 2017-04-09\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| IEM Sydney 2017\n| [[Sydney]], [[Australia]]\n| 2017-05-03 {{ndash}} 2017-05-07\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| ECS Season 3 Finals\n| London, Unitd Kingdom\n| 2017-06-23 {{ndash}} 2017-06-25\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" |With 2018's ENCE Esports\n|-\n| {{Gold1}}\n| StarSeries & i-League CS:GO Season 6 \n| Kiev, Ukraine\n| 2018-10-07 {{ndash}} 2018-10-14\n|-\n| {{Gold1}}\n| Dreamhack Open Winter 2018\n| [[J\u00f6nk\u00f6ping]], [[Sweden]]\n| 2018-11-30 {{ndash}} 2018-12-02\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| [[Intel Extreme Masters Season XIII \u2013 World Championship Major|IEM Katowice 2019]]\n| Katowice, Poland\n| 2019-02-13 {{ndash}} 2019-03-03\n|-\n| {{Gold1}}\n| BLAST Pro Series: Madrid 2019 \n| [[Madrid]], [[Spain]]\n| 2019-05-10 {{ndash}} 2019-05-11\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| DreamHack Masters Dallas 2019  \n| [[Dallas]], [[United States]]\n| 2019-05-28 {{ndash}} 2019-06-02\n|-\n| {{Silver2}}\n| IEM Chicago 2019\n| [[Chicago]], United States\n| 